&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The thyroid gland &lt;/strong&gt;uses iodine from food to make two thyroid hormones: &lt;strong&gt;triiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It also stores these thyroid hormones and releases them as they are needed. The hypothalamus and the pituitary gland, which are located in the brain, help control the thyroid gland.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hypothalamus releases thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH), which stimulates the pituitary gland to release thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). When the hypothalamus and pituitary are working normally, they sense when:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thyroid hormone levels are low, so they secrete more TRH and TSH, which stimulates the thyroid to make more hormones.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thyroid hormone levels are too high, so they secrete less TRH and TSH, which reduces hormone production&amp;nbsp;by the thyroid.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, we can say that the &lt;strong&gt;Hormone released from the thyroid is&amp;nbsp;thyroxine.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Insulin&lt;/span&gt;: It&amp;nbsp;is a hormone made in the pancreas. It controls the amount of glucose in our bloodstream. It also helps store glucose in your liver, fat, and muscles. It also regulates our body&amp;rsquo;s metabolism of carbohydrates, fats, and proteins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The thyroid gland is a vital hormone gland playing a major role in the metabolism, growth, and development of the human body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The thyroid gland produces three hormones:-
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Triiodothyronine, known as T3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thyroxine (Tetraiodothyronine), known as T4&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Calcitonin&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Please note that&amp;nbsp;Iodine is one of the main building blocks of T3 and T4.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hyperthyroidism&lt;/strong&gt; (overactive thyroid) occurs when your thyroid gland produces too much of the hormone thyroxine.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hyperthyroidism can accelerate your body&amp;#39;s metabolism, causing unintentional weight loss and a rapid or irregular heartbeat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The body can also produce too little thyroxine.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;all of the above&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Boiling&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;It is the rapid vaporization of a liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When raw vegetables are immersed in boiling water, vegetables start to get cooked.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid is equal to the pressure exerted on the liquid by the surrounding atmosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stewing&lt;/strong&gt;: It is a cooking method. It uses small, uniform pieces of raw food immersed in a liquid and slowly simmered. It involves&amp;nbsp;a very slow boiling of water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Simmering&lt;/strong&gt;: It is a cooking method&amp;nbsp;in which foods are cooked in hot liquids kept just below the boiling point of water.&lt;/li&gt;
